## Context
The NCC piece argues: climate finance crystallized around Copenhagen (2009),
not Paris (2015), and the conceptual categories haven't changed since. This
is a strong claim for a high-visibility venue. Before drafting, we need to
know what the existing literature says about periodization, category
stability, and the relationship between policy events and scholarly structure.

## Actions
1. Survey existing periodizations of climate finance in the literature
   (Care & Weber 2023, Shang & Jin 2023, Maria et al 2023, others)
2. Identify who (if anyone) has argued Paris was a structural break in
   scholarship (not just policy)
3. Find work on "category stability" or "conceptual lock-in" in STS/HPS
   that supports or challenges our finding
4. Check NCC's recent publications on climate finance governance — what
   framing resonates with their editors?
5. Identify the 3-5 papers the NCC piece must cite to position itself

## Test
Annotated bibliography of 10-20 key references with notes on how each
relates to our argument.

## Exit criteria
Clear picture of where our finding sits in the literature. Key references
identified. Gaps or vulnerabilities in the argument flagged.
